  "prompt": "What is the difference between a notarized and certified document?",
  "response": "Notarized and certified documents serve different purposes and involve different processes. Here\u2019s a breakdown of the differences:\n\n### **Certified Document**\n- **Definition**: A certified document is a copy of an original document that has been verified as true and accurate by an authorized person or entity.\n- **Purpose**: It is often used to provide official proof or evidence of the original document\u2019s authenticity.\n- **Process**: \n  - The certifying authority (e.g., a government office, school, or lawyer) compares the copy to the original document.\n  - They stamp, sign, or attach a statement confirming that the copy is a true and accurate representation of the original.\n- **Common Examples**: Certified copies of birth certificates, marriage certificates, academic transcripts, or legal documents.\n- **Authority**: The certifier must have the legal authority or professional standing to certify the document.\n\n### **Notarized Document**\n- **Definition**: A notarized document is one that has been verified by a notary public, who confirms the identity of the person signing the document and ensures they are signing voluntarily.\n- **Purpose**: It is used to prevent fraud and ensure the authenticity of signatures on legal documents.\n- **Process**:\n  - The signer appears before a notary public and provides proof of identity.\n  - The notary witnesses the signing of the document and adds their official seal or stamp.\n  - The notary may also administer an oath or affirmation, depending on the document.\n- **Common Examples**: Affidavits, deeds, powers of attorney, loan agreements, or contracts.\n- **Authority**: Only a licensed notary public can notarize a document.\n\n### **Key Differences**\n| **Aspect**             | **Certified Document**                              | **Notarized Document**                               |\n|-------------------------|----------------------------------------------------|-----------------------------------------------------|\n| **Purpose**             | Verifies the accuracy of a copy of the original.   | Verifies the identity of the signer and their voluntary consent. |\n| **Who Performs It**     | Authorized entity (e.g., government office, lawyer). | Notary public.                                      |\n| **Focus**               | Document authenticity.                            | Signature authenticity and signer\u2019s identity.       |\n| **Common Use Cases**    | Copies of official records (e.g., birth certificates). | Legal documents requiring signatures (e.g., contracts). |\n\nIn summary, certification focuses on the document itself, while notarization focuses on the person signing the document.",
  "temperature": 1.0,
